I'm Philip Cloud.

00:00:56.320 --> 00:01:00.480
I work on a project called Ibis at Voltron Data.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.639
I've been doing this sort of work with tabular data tools for about 10 or more years.

00:01:07.760 --> 00:01:10.000
You can find me at these places on the internet.

00:01:11.360 --> 00:01:13.680
And the question we're sort of going to address here is,

00:01:14.480 --> 00:01:16.400
have you ever needed to test a complex system?

00:01:17.120 --> 00:01:22.800
Um, so there was a handful of things you might have encountered while needing to test a complex

00:01:22.800 --> 00:01:23.519
system.

00:01:23.519 --> 00:01:24.800
One of them is Docker.

00:01:25.519 --> 00:01:33.120
Um, you probably, uh, have also encountered Python packaging as a challenge in some way.

00:01:34.720 --> 00:01:40.080
Or maybe you don't care about tests and you just are like, screw it.

00:01:40.080 --> 00:01:42.080
Everything works the first time I write it.

00:01:42.959 --> 00:01:45.519
And I don't need to run it anywhere else except my laptop.

00:01:47.279 --> 00:01:53.120
So one, one complex system that I work on every day is called Ibis.

00:01:53.120 --> 00:01:57.199
And I'm going to talk a little bit about it and then we're going to delve into the testing bits.

00:01:58.639 --> 00:02:02.239
So Ibis is a Python library for exploratory data analysis,

00:02:02.239 --> 00:02:05.680
general tabular data munging, data engineering, MLP processing.

00:02:06.320 --> 00:02:09.600
And I think probably for a lot of people in this room,

00:02:10.399 --> 00:02:12.639
the analogy of dbplyr will make sense.

00:02:12.639 --> 00:02:15.679
And so it's like dbplyr, but it's Python.

00:02:16.399 --> 00:02:17.440
So what does that look like?

00:02:19.839 --> 00:02:23.360
Uh, it's kind of one API and 20 backends.

00:02:23.360 --> 00:02:24.720
I think, I think we're at 20.

00:02:24.720 --> 00:02:25.759
I don't remember.

00:02:25.759 --> 00:02:30.160
Um, and you can kind of, you can see like we support a bunch of stuff.

00:02:30.720 --> 00:02:36.160
This is, this is a reading a parquet file, doing a group by an account, nothing earth shattering.

00:02:36.720 --> 00:02:42.080
And you can see that when I go from DuckDB to Polars to DataFusion to PySpark,

00:02:43.360 --> 00:02:45.839
it, uh, well, it's not actually showing up on the slides.

00:02:46.479 --> 00:02:46.979
Okay.

00:02:47.520 --> 00:02:50.880
Maybe it's cause I'm not clicking in the right place.

00:02:51.520 --> 00:02:52.020
There we go.

00:02:52.720 --> 00:02:55.520
Polars to DataFusion to PySpark.

00:02:55.520 --> 00:02:58.479
Things kind of, you know, they kind of look the same, right?

00:02:58.479 --> 00:03:00.720
The first line is the only thing that's changing.

00:03:01.919 --> 00:03:05.440
And, you know, when we get to the rest of the backends,

00:03:07.199 --> 00:03:09.679
things start to look kind of like this.

00:03:10.639 --> 00:03:16.639
Um, you as the user don't see this crazy Rube Goldberg machine thing.

00:03:17.360 --> 00:03:21.360
Um, but, but as developers of this project, like this is sort of what it looks like,

00:03:21.360 --> 00:03:25.199
you know, like there's a guy putting a ball into a conveyor belt and

00:03:25.199 --> 00:03:29.600
there's like a TV saying, no, things get weird.

00:03:32.160 --> 00:03:32.660
Okay.

00:03:33.839 --> 00:03:37.600
So, uh, maybe you've already had this thought already,

00:03:37.600 --> 00:03:39.279
but like, why is this hard to test?

00:03:39.279 --> 00:03:42.479
And just a few facts about Ibis.

00:03:42.479 --> 00:03:46.960
We've got 17 SQL backends, three non-SQL, two of them run in the cloud.

00:03:47.839 --> 00:03:50.960
Nine of the SQL ones are like distributed and run in a cluster.

00:03:51.520 --> 00:03:54.800
Um, three of the backends don't have anything to do with SQL at all.

00:03:54.800 --> 00:03:56.800
They're just DataFrame APIs.

00:03:56.800 --> 00:04:00.240
We support a backend that is 40, that is 45 years old.

00:04:00.240 --> 00:04:02.240
It was written 45 years ago.

00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:02.960
It's Oracle.

00:04:03.440 --> 00:04:07.759
Um, we have the youngest backend is called RisingWave.

00:04:07.759 --> 00:04:11.039
It's a streaming SQL backend and it is about two years old.

00:04:11.679 --> 00:04:12.960
Latency is all over the place.

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:16.880
We've got stuff going, you know, to, from, you know, New York to

00:04:16.880 --> 00:04:19.760
Singapore and we've got DuckDB running on a laptop.

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:24.559
So things are kind of weird all over the place and deployment varies, right?

00:04:24.559 --> 00:04:29.040
Somebody might be running a cluster of, you know, a thousand nodes of Trino on a,

00:04:29.040 --> 00:04:32.880
you know, Kubernetes, or you might be running Polars on your laptop.

00:04:34.320 --> 00:04:36.399
And on top of that, we still have to develop features.

00:04:36.399 --> 00:04:39.200
We're not sitting around writing tests all day, right?

00:04:39.760 --> 00:04:41.920
Although it might feel like that after this talk.

00:04:42.959 --> 00:04:46.799
Um, so we're, we're sort of in a bit of a pickle here trying to test 20 databases.

00:04:47.519 --> 00:04:50.320
So how do we, how do we manage this complexity?

00:04:51.359 --> 00:04:55.279
Um, well, there's, there's like basically one high-level goal,

00:04:55.279 --> 00:04:57.519
which is to iterate quickly.

00:04:57.519 --> 00:05:00.640
And that's sort of project dependent, but we found that there are a few

00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:02.880
things that really matter when trying to do this.

00:05:02.880 --> 00:05:06.320
And one is that your environment setup needs to be fast,

00:05:06.320 --> 00:05:09.440
because if you're going to run this stuff in continuous integration,

00:05:09.440 --> 00:05:13.359
like say on GitHub actions, you don't want to spend a bunch of your time

00:05:14.320 --> 00:05:15.760
solving dependency constraints.

00:05:16.399 --> 00:05:20.959
Um, by the way, a lot of this stuff is not stuff that we started out knowing, right?

00:05:20.959 --> 00:05:23.440
But we were like, Oh, our environment setup needs to be fast.

00:05:23.440 --> 00:05:25.839
It was more like, Oh, this is really slow.

00:05:26.399 --> 00:05:27.440
And here's what we've learned.

00:05:28.799 --> 00:05:30.480
Your tests also need to be fast.

00:05:30.799 --> 00:05:34.799
Don't run tbch scale factor a thousand in a unit test.

00:05:37.279 --> 00:05:41.279
In our case, we have all these backends and their tests, like running their tests

00:05:41.279 --> 00:05:42.640
should not depend on each other, right?

00:05:42.640 --> 00:05:46.079
If I want to test like the, you know, the, the DuckDB backend,

00:05:46.079 --> 00:05:48.959
I shouldn't have to wait for the Postgres test to also finish.

00:05:50.480 --> 00:05:54.559
And then running these things like running, say the Postgres backend

00:05:54.559 --> 00:05:56.160
locally needs to be easy, right?

00:05:56.160 --> 00:05:59.920
You don't want to have like a 10 sub command long Docker compose command.

00:06:00.959 --> 00:06:02.799
To like spin up a Postgres server.

00:06:03.679 --> 00:06:06.320
So we use something called just, which is a task runner.

00:06:06.320 --> 00:06:09.920
It's kind of like make without make where all the targets are phony.

00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:12.640
If you don't know what that means, I'm happy to talk your ear off about it later.

00:06:14.720 --> 00:06:16.239
CI must complete quickly.

00:06:16.239 --> 00:06:18.480
Continuous integration must finish fast.

00:06:20.399 --> 00:06:24.959
So the tools that we use are, we use poetry for dependency management.

00:06:24.959 --> 00:06:28.399
If somebody wants to come berate me for that later, happy to talk about that too.

00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:31.040
Um, we use GitHub actions.

00:06:31.040 --> 00:06:32.640
The project is hosted on GitHub.

00:06:32.640 --> 00:06:37.600
It's just easier than any alternative at the moment for a big backends.

00:06:37.600 --> 00:06:39.920
And I say big, I don't mean necessarily scale,

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:42.079
but their complexity of deployment.

00:06:42.079 --> 00:06:46.399
We use Docker, Docker compose for the small backends.

00:06:46.399 --> 00:06:47.760
They don't really get any special treatment.

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:52.480
You just sort of run them, you know, on whatever machine they happen to be running on.

00:06:52.480 --> 00:06:57.519
And then, like I said, for tasks sort of, you know, just do X, just whatever.

00:06:57.519 --> 00:06:59.119
The tool is literally called just.

00:07:00.239 --> 00:07:02.079
And so why do we use poetry?

00:07:03.839 --> 00:07:05.679
To make environments set up fast.

00:07:07.359 --> 00:07:12.880
Solving like satisfiability constraint problems in CI is a terrible, terrible idea.

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:14.880
This is what we used to do.

00:07:14.880 --> 00:07:17.119
And it turned out that we turned out to be a bad idea.

00:07:17.119 --> 00:07:18.720
We were like, Hey, why is our CI slow?

00:07:18.720 --> 00:07:20.720
Well, our tests aren't actually slow.

00:07:20.720 --> 00:07:24.079
We're just like solving this massive constraint problem.

00:07:24.079 --> 00:07:26.959
Every single time a commit is pushed to me.

00:07:27.760 --> 00:07:29.200
So poetry is one way to do this.

00:07:30.720 --> 00:07:33.040
Generally, the principle here is like get a lock file.

00:07:33.760 --> 00:07:38.000
And a lock file is essentially a giant list of pin dependencies.

00:07:39.119 --> 00:07:42.480
And so maybe one of the downsides is, okay, well, I can't test.

00:07:43.679 --> 00:07:48.160
Maybe I can't test every single, you know, constraint that I could possibly come up with.

00:07:48.160 --> 00:07:50.239
But like the question is like, are you doing that now?

00:07:50.880 --> 00:07:53.679
And if you are, I would really like to know about how you are doing.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:55.040
Mentioned Docker.

00:07:56.239 --> 00:08:00.559
I've seen setups for more complex, tested, more complex projects where people

00:08:00.559 --> 00:08:02.720
have like a Docker setup for local stuff.

00:08:02.720 --> 00:08:07.440
And then they have a Docker setup for CI and they don't match exactly.

00:08:07.440 --> 00:08:12.239
And then, then you sort of get like works on my machine, you know, syndrome.

00:08:12.239 --> 00:08:12.880
That's not great.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:19.760
So really here, we found that using Docker exactly how you would use it locally in CI

00:08:19.760 --> 00:08:21.519
really helped like cut down on that.

00:08:21.519 --> 00:08:21.920
Bugs.

00:08:21.920 --> 00:08:24.880
And ultimately when we did get bugs was more reproducible.

00:08:26.079 --> 00:08:29.839
If you're using dot compose, there's health checks and you can use really dumb ones.

00:08:29.839 --> 00:08:35.840
Like just curl the thing at, you know, basically any, any address that it can listen on.

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:40.479
You know, you can use like Netcat to check if a port is open on a particular address.

00:08:40.479 --> 00:08:44.400
Like that's often enough or send, you know, select one plus one to your database every

00:08:44.400 --> 00:08:44.960
five seconds.

00:08:46.559 --> 00:08:48.000
And it's gotta be easy for people to use.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:52.320
I keep saying that, but it's like really important that people don't have to write,

00:08:52.320 --> 00:08:55.440
remember a Docker compose command and then seven environment variables.

00:08:55.440 --> 00:08:59.359
And then like, oh, you gotta have this file here and this directory here and that plate.

00:08:59.359 --> 00:09:00.320
Like, no.

00:09:03.039 --> 00:09:08.799
GitHub actions, not a whole lot here, but we ended up paying for what's called the team's

00:09:08.799 --> 00:09:12.960
plan, which is just a way to run more stuff at the same time.

00:09:12.960 --> 00:09:14.799
And it's not particularly expensive.

00:09:14.799 --> 00:09:20.880
We spend $624 a year for a team of like eight developers to work on Ibis full time.

00:09:22.960 --> 00:09:25.520
So how does this, how does this like sort of stack up?

00:09:26.960 --> 00:09:31.359
Like what do we do to actually figure out whether any of this stuff was working well?

00:09:33.760 --> 00:09:34.719
Bit of terminology.

00:09:37.200 --> 00:09:39.599
A job is like a set of commands.

00:09:39.599 --> 00:09:42.320
So it, we have a job that is a set of commands.

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:44.000
Job is like a set of commands.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:49.039
So it roughly corresponds to like all the things you would need to do to test one Ibis

00:09:49.039 --> 00:09:49.520
backend.

00:09:50.479 --> 00:09:55.599
So it's like pip install Ibis, you know, run your tests, upload coverage, that sort of

00:09:55.599 --> 00:09:55.840
thing.

00:09:56.880 --> 00:10:00.640
And then you've got workflows, which are essentially a collection of those jobs.

00:10:00.640 --> 00:10:06.320
And so our sort of main workflow that is the biggest bottleneck in our test suite, it contains

00:10:07.359 --> 00:10:10.159
the, you know, basically a job for every single backend.

00:10:11.119 --> 00:10:12.640
Oh, it's not actually written that way.

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:13.599
We can talk about that later.

00:10:14.880 --> 00:10:16.400
So we measured some stuff.

00:10:17.599 --> 00:10:22.799
And one of the things that we measured that turned out to be really useful was the average

00:10:22.799 --> 00:10:23.520
job duration.

00:10:24.159 --> 00:10:26.320
Not a particularly complicated thing to look at.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:35.119
But here you can actually see that sort of pre-poetry, we had this weird U thing, not

00:10:35.119 --> 00:10:36.559
entirely sure what's going on there.

00:10:37.520 --> 00:10:41.440
There's like this, you know, there's this line that looks like, you know, it's like,

00:10:41.440 --> 00:10:42.559
oh, trending downward.

00:10:42.559 --> 00:10:43.760
And it's like, not really.

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:47.440
And variability is all over the place.

00:10:47.440 --> 00:10:51.200
Once we switched to poetry, we see that there was kind of a step change in our average

00:10:51.200 --> 00:10:51.679
duration.

00:10:52.559 --> 00:10:56.320
And that was great, which allowed us to run more and more jobs concurrently.

00:10:56.320 --> 00:10:59.760
And so we can, you know, if we wanted to add some more backends, it would be great.

00:10:59.760 --> 00:11:01.280
We can run stuff concurrently.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:03.440
Variability dropped quite a bit.

00:11:04.239 --> 00:11:08.960
And then when we went to the sort of added the ability to do more concurrency, there

00:11:08.960 --> 00:11:13.280
wasn't a huge effect on average job duration because that doesn't actually help with that

00:11:13.280 --> 00:11:13.599
problem.

00:11:14.719 --> 00:11:21.039
This is like about making your actual individual sort of test this backend thing faster.

00:11:22.880 --> 00:11:27.919
And like, since we've switched to poetry in the team plan, like we've added three or four

00:11:27.919 --> 00:11:32.559
new backends and it's roughly stayed the same, which is pretty nice.

00:11:34.080 --> 00:11:36.239
So that's jobs.

00:11:36.239 --> 00:11:37.200
What about workflows?

00:11:37.840 --> 00:11:42.799
So for workflows, we've got queuing time, which is very important.

00:11:42.799 --> 00:11:48.960
It's a good measure of basically how long your individual jobs are waiting to run.

00:11:48.960 --> 00:11:49.280
Right.

00:11:49.280 --> 00:11:56.320
And you might be like, oh, well, before poetry, like things were better and it's only because

00:11:56.320 --> 00:11:58.719
we just weren't running that many jobs.

00:11:58.719 --> 00:11:58.960
Right.

00:11:59.599 --> 00:12:04.159
But the ones that we were running, like you can see in the plot below the workflow duration,

00:12:04.880 --> 00:12:06.239
they were all over the place.

00:12:06.239 --> 00:12:06.640
Right.

00:12:06.640 --> 00:12:08.000
So not a whole lot of jobs.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:11.440
So the queue, so the queue was like when a thing came in, it was like, boom, kicked it

00:12:11.440 --> 00:12:12.000
off, ran.

00:12:12.799 --> 00:12:15.280
But when it did run, it took forever to run.

00:12:16.960 --> 00:12:20.239
Or it took, you know, a lot of, it was, it was sort of unpredictable.

00:12:21.359 --> 00:12:25.520
And then you can see once we moved to poetry, like, okay, queuing time seems to have sort

00:12:25.520 --> 00:12:26.719
of gone up a bit.

00:12:26.719 --> 00:12:31.359
And that was actually because we were able to run more stuff at the same time.

00:12:32.400 --> 00:12:35.280
And that's when we were like, okay, well, maybe we should get more concurrency now.

00:12:35.280 --> 00:12:38.880
So that's when we switched the team plan and things like sort of happily went back down

00:12:38.880 --> 00:12:42.239
closer to that original queuing time.

00:12:43.520 --> 00:12:47.359
There's sort of this weird swell going on in, in workflow duration.

00:12:47.359 --> 00:12:49.119
Haven't really figured out what's going on there.

00:12:51.359 --> 00:12:54.320
But yeah, so that's, that's workflow metrics.

00:12:54.320 --> 00:12:59.359
And, and this is sort of like a different view on that, which is, which is maybe makes

00:12:59.359 --> 00:13:05.760
the, the relationship between workflow duration and queuing time a bit more obvious, like

00:13:05.760 --> 00:13:06.640
when things get weird.

00:13:06.640 --> 00:13:11.840
So you can kind of see at the bottom of the left plot that like, you've got this line

00:13:11.840 --> 00:13:18.400
at zero, which is like tons of workflows are slow, but queuing time is really fast.

00:13:18.400 --> 00:13:22.640
So that's like maybe an indication you should look into making your jobs individually faster.

00:13:23.599 --> 00:13:27.119
And then on the right, that's sort of what this, the same data look like after we switched

00:13:27.119 --> 00:13:29.840
to poetry and increased concurrency.

00:13:31.679 --> 00:13:35.919
And things are, we've still got a couple of outliers that need to be debugged a bit, but

00:13:35.919 --> 00:13:41.200
we're, we're in a much better place where things are, are, are both more correlated

00:13:41.200 --> 00:13:42.640
and sort of shallower.

00:13:45.280 --> 00:13:51.039
So the kind of moral, moral of the story here-ish is that you kind of want queues and workflows

00:13:51.039 --> 00:13:52.320
to be correlated.

00:13:52.400 --> 00:13:57.280
Now that's not actually enough because you can just have really long queuing time and

00:13:57.280 --> 00:14:02.239
really slow jobs until they'll be perfectly correlated potentially.

00:14:02.880 --> 00:14:07.679
But you don't want to see things where you've got a vertical line, you know, here or a horizontal

00:14:07.679 --> 00:14:08.640
line there.

00:14:09.840 --> 00:14:14.000
So if queues are slow and workflows are fast, you probably don't have enough concurrency.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:18.559
If your queues are fast and workflows are slow, you probably need to look at your individual

00:14:18.559 --> 00:14:20.159
like sort of CI jobs.

00:14:20.400 --> 00:14:25.200
And then if both are slow, it's sort of hard to say, you probably have slow jobs that you're

00:14:25.200 --> 00:14:26.479
trying to run a lot of.

00:14:27.599 --> 00:14:28.799
So you kind of need to look into that.

00:14:30.719 --> 00:14:31.219
Okay.

00:14:31.679 --> 00:14:37.599
So to summarize, testing complex projects as possible, use Docker for both dev and prod,

00:14:37.599 --> 00:14:39.359
don't have two different setups for that.

00:14:40.080 --> 00:14:42.320
Don't solve satisfiability problems in CI.

00:14:44.239 --> 00:14:50.080
Measure stuff about the things you care about, and then also spend some time on the

00:14:51.039 --> 00:14:52.960
easy to run the complicated things.

00:14:55.520 --> 00:14:56.020
That's it.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:02.799
Thank you, Philip.

00:15:03.760 --> 00:15:06.640
And actually, we have a couple minutes for some questions from the crowd.

00:15:06.640 --> 00:15:08.239
So yeah, we'll start off.

00:15:09.200 --> 00:15:12.239
I'm an R programmer who would like to use Python for data wrangling.

00:15:13.039 --> 00:15:15.119
Emily recommended learning Polars.

00:15:15.119 --> 00:15:19.039
Would you recommend I use Ibis with a Polars backend?

00:15:20.960 --> 00:15:22.479
Tough question right off the bat.

00:15:22.479 --> 00:15:22.979
Okay.

